The two carboxylic acid groups (one as a COOH and the other part of the core structure) significantly increase the melting point due to the strong hydrogen bonding they enable, which is estimated to raise the melting point by about +100 degrees each. The presence of two aromatic rings contributes further stability and higher molecular weight, increasing the melting point by about +35 degrees each. The amide linkage (Nc1 in SMILES) also contributes to increased melting point through hydrogen bonding and resonance stability, adding about +40 degrees. However, one of the carboxylic acid functionalities is part of the interconnected aromatic system and its effect has been partially accounted for in the addition from the aromatic rings. Therefore, we will consider only one separate +100-degree addition for the standalone carboxylic acid group. The methyl groups (indicated by 'C' at the end of the SMILES) slightly increase the molecular weight, each contributing approximately +5 degrees to the melting point.
Prediction: 5.5 (basic benzene unit) + 200 (carboxylic acids) + 70 (aromatic rings) + 40 (amide linkage) + 10 (methyl groups) = 325.5°C
